&gt;&gt; Avner Moriah: Thank
you for having me.

00:06:58.470 --> 00:07:04.200
It's a great honor to be here,
and going to put my watch here

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:09.510
so I make sure that we keep
the time schedule right.

00:07:09.510 --> 00:07:15.060
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:19.340
I'm going to take you through a
quick journey through my work,

00:07:19.340 --> 00:07:23.050
and then we will concentrate
on the project

00:07:23.050 --> 00:07:25.680
that I'm working on right now.

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:27.830
Actually, I've been working on it

00:07:27.830 --> 00:07:31.310
for the last 15 years is
"Illuminating the Text".

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:38.660
I didn't start as an illustrator,
but I came about this project

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:42.300
from painting the Israeli
landscape and other things.

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:47.620
So, I'm going to give you a quick
run of how I go to where I go.

00:07:47.620 --> 00:07:53.330
So, what you see here is
works of mine from '78.

00:07:53.330 --> 00:07:54.830
I was a student at Bazalel.

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:58.590
I, I'm a graduate of
Bazalel Academy of Art,

00:07:58.590 --> 00:08:03.400
and Yale University
MFA program there.

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:08.590
These are landscapes that I
painted in the Judean hills.

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:16.330
This is a series that I did on
Israeli soldiers in the landscape.

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:25.290
With [inaudible] of camouflage
behind it that what got me to work

00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:30.380
on the subsequent was
the idea of camouflage.

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:36.300
This, I did a large
series on the holocaust,

00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:40.790
and what inspired me there
was the movie "Shoah".

00:08:40.790 --> 00:08:46.650 position:56%
My dear, with this subject matter is
usually we paint either the victims

00:08:46.650 --> 00:08:52.360
or the perpetrators, and
I chose to paint both

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:57.850
because by putting the perpetrators
and the victims together in one,

00:08:57.850 --> 00:09:03.330
on one canvas extends the
horror that actually took place.

00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:06.740
I, whenever I do a
series of paintings,

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:11.470
I tend to go and do
serious research.

00:09:11.470 --> 00:09:17.600 position:56%
I went to Germany to look at the
works, the German expressionist work

00:09:17.600 --> 00:09:19.110
that was done before the war,

00:09:19.110 --> 00:09:23.310
and you can really sense
that the war is coming.

00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:25.900
So, this is my stadium.

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:30.110
This is the dining hall.

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:34.210
This is a series that I did on the
expulsion of the Jews from Spain.

00:09:34.210 --> 00:09:38.990
Again, I went to Spain and looked
at the art that was done in Spain,

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:43.040
and what was interesting
that right around 1492,

00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:45.410
you see a tremendous
amount of search

00:09:45.410 --> 00:09:49.650
in the churches that
were all renovated.

00:09:49.650 --> 00:09:56.800 position:56%
And so, when you come to think about
it, it was either from money or gold

00:09:56.800 --> 00:10:05.920
that came from South America or
money that came from the Muslims

00:10:05.920 --> 00:10:09.570
or the Jews where the
church said to them,

00:10:09.570 --> 00:10:13.160
"Prove to us that you're good
members of the community."

00:10:13.160 --> 00:10:18.970
So, this is looting the synagogue.

00:10:18.970 --> 00:10:21.300
For years, I've been painting
the Israeli landscape.

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:23.370
This is the Mount Sinai.

00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:27.320
I actually went to paint
next to Mount Sinai,

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:30.140
and I have a small
anecdote about it.

00:10:30.140 --> 00:10:33.790
It is but when I stood and painted
there, in order to get to the point

00:10:33.790 --> 00:10:39.880
that I wanted to paint, you
had to pass an Egyptian post,

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:44.810
and there was an officer
that was standing there.

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:47.280
And, for five days, he let me go.

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:49.500
After five days, he
wanted baksheesh.

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:52.110
But the Bedouins came to him
and said, "He's a good painter.

00:10:52.110 --> 00:10:53.410
Let him paint."

00:10:53.410 --> 00:10:55.560
So, I didn't have to pay anything.

00:10:55.560 --> 00:11:00.550
So, that's just like a
nice human interaction.

00:11:00.550 --> 00:11:03.710
These are all landscapes
that I paint on site.

00:11:03.710 --> 00:11:05.100
These are large canvases.

00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:07.890
They're 42 inches by 80 inches.

00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:17.830
This is a sunset over the Sea
of Galilee with a Khamsin winds.

00:11:17.830 --> 00:11:19.500
These are views of Jerusalem.

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:21.400
I'll just go quickly
through it so we can get

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:23.970
to the point where I want to.

00:11:28.060 --> 00:11:29.700
This is a painting of my wife.

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:33.800
She passed away five years ago.

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:36.890
She was the inspiration
of my Bible project,

00:11:36.890 --> 00:11:39.330
the one that I'm working on now.

00:11:39.330 --> 00:11:45.750
What got me into dealing with the
Jewish text was an opportunity

00:11:45.750 --> 00:11:47.050
that I got from JPS.

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:51.100
I did two large murals for them.

00:11:51.100 --> 00:11:56.200 position:56%
The first one that you see here is,
I did a big project on the gathering

00:11:56.200 --> 00:12:03.170
at Mount Sinai, and when we
looked for a place to do my mural

00:12:03.170 --> 00:12:06.700
at the JPS, they said,
"Find any place

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:08.000
that you want in the building."

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.870
So, I chose the staircase
that leads to the library,

00:12:11.870 --> 00:12:17.390
and I thought of places that
we go up and down in the bible.

00:12:17.390 --> 00:12:20.790
And, I thought of Mount
Sinai because at Mount Sinai,

00:12:20.790 --> 00:12:26.000
we got the written
word and the, also.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:31.350
So, and there are other cases
of going up and down the ladder,

00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:35.290
like Joseph in the
pit or Jacob's ladder.

00:12:35.290 --> 00:12:39.260
The number ten occurred
because we have the ten plagues

00:12:39.260 --> 00:12:40.810
and the ten commandments.

00:12:40.810 --> 00:12:45.210 position:56%
I thought of the ten Rabbis that
were executed by the Romans and the,

00:12:45.210 --> 00:12:49.280
and I thought also of ten
[inaudible] that dealt

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:52.430
with the gathering at Mount Sinai.

00:12:52.430 --> 00:12:56.840 position:56%
So, the centerpiece is the different
times that we went, that Moses goes

00:12:56.840 --> 00:12:58.140
up and down the mountain.

00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:02.500
I mean, there's more than one
story about getting the Torah.

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:07.620
And, the other panels around
are the different points

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:09.330
that I just mentioned.

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:17.560
And, after I finished these murals,
people came to me and said, "Oh,

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:18.860
you should do a Haggadah.

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:22.000
You should do a Haggadah,
now, so I just finished the.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.610
So, this actually worked,
coincided with the first round

00:13:25.610 --> 00:13:30.690
of my wife battling cancer, and I
thought of the Passover Haggadah

00:13:30.690 --> 00:13:36.090
because we all go in
and out of Egypt.

00:13:36.090 --> 00:13:37.980
And, this is one of the pages

00:13:37.980 --> 00:13:41.230
that Jerusalem is the
center of the universe.

00:13:41.230 --> 00:13:43.900
Actually, here, it's
interesting because the image

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:49.060
that I used was a painting
from Piero della Francesca,

00:13:49.060 --> 00:13:51.070
"Resurrection of Christ",

00:13:51.070 --> 00:13:54.920
and the resurrection
also deals with Passover.

00:13:54.920 --> 00:14:02.760
This is, again, an image
from the Passover Haggadah.

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:06.230
When I, when I did these series, I
worked, again, very methodically.

00:14:06.230 --> 00:14:10.560
I did the many, many
drawings, many, many studies,

00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:13.740
and then I sit together
with my calligrapher.

00:14:13.740 --> 00:14:17.480
I'm totally dyslexic, so I don't
even come close to writing text

00:14:17.480 --> 00:14:22.210
because the letters
have their own life.

00:14:22.210 --> 00:14:26.320
So, we design page after
page with my images,

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:27.620
and I do everything twice.

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:30.500 position:56%
I first do the preliminary studies,
and then I sit with the calligrapher

00:14:30.500 --> 00:14:34.300
and we design page after
page with text and image.

00:14:34.300 --> 00:14:41.730
These are images, after I finish
this, I have a friend in New York.

00:14:41.730 --> 00:14:44.570
She is a curator of a museum.

00:14:44.570 --> 00:14:55.350
She said, "Oh, you should
do something more cheerful.

00:14:55.350 --> 00:15:01.350
How about doing some work about
[Hebrew language]" Like, tales.

00:15:01.350 --> 00:15:07.450
So, so, I thought of the
scroll of Esther because it's,

00:15:07.450 --> 00:15:10.140
she thought more like
Hansel and Gretel

00:15:10.140 --> 00:15:12.560 position:56%
than stories like that, but I chose.

00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:18.640
And so, again, I went
and I studied the tale

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:21.950
of Esther or the scroll of Esther.

00:15:21.950 --> 00:15:32.920
And, I created 76 images where
I paint the visual story.

00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:37.310
I think one of the gifts
that I've been given

00:15:37.310 --> 00:15:43.200
from whoever gives those gifts is
my ability to, when I read a text,

00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:45.420
to come up with a set design.

00:15:45.420 --> 00:15:48.890
That's why I showed you my
other works to see how I create

00:15:48.890 --> 00:15:54.210
like a set design from
something that is abstract,

00:15:54.210 --> 00:15:59.550 position:56%
but if you give me very few details,
I can come with my own design so,

00:15:59.550 --> 00:16:01.820
and I work, again,
here very methodically.

00:16:01.820 --> 00:16:05.810
I looked at Persian
miniatures, Indian miniatures,

00:16:05.810 --> 00:16:09.580
and I always make a point
about making that I live

00:16:09.580 --> 00:16:11.400
and work in the Middle East.

00:16:11.400 --> 00:16:16.270
So, although you could see
that there's a three dimension,

00:16:16.270 --> 00:16:20.510
but I also use the two
dimension design even

00:16:20.510 --> 00:16:22.780
in my holocaust paintings.

00:16:22.780 --> 00:16:29.200
When I did them, I, there
are three ideas that I had.

00:16:29.200 --> 00:16:32.850
One is called "The Dance of Death".

00:16:32.850 --> 00:16:37.030
That's a Nordic theme that
deals with mass killings.

00:16:37.030 --> 00:16:39.980
And, it was during the 100 year war

00:16:39.980 --> 00:16:43.030
between the Protestants
and the Catholics.

00:16:43.030 --> 00:16:48.540
Also, there's a theme in Italian
southern theme that is called

00:16:48.540 --> 00:16:49.870
"The Massacre of the Innocents".

00:16:49.870 --> 00:16:52.740
They actually painted the
destruction of the temple.

00:16:52.740 --> 00:16:55.100
And then, I paint, I
thought of Egyptian art

00:16:55.100 --> 00:16:57.370
because they deal with
life after death.

00:16:57.370 --> 00:16:59.850
And, I combined all
these images together

00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:03.760
to create my own interpretation
of the text.

